explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER — This macro is the primary control-flow concern: it may contain an early return, abort, exit, longjmp, or other non-local control transfer. To determine whether the subsequent code is unreachable you must inspect its definition/expansion. OS_ObjectIdGetById — The function sets return_code from this call and the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) test depends on the possible return values from this function; you need its behavior/return semantics to know if the branch (and thus the call to the Impl function) can be reached. OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl — The call inside the guarded branch; include its prototype to confirm it is a normal callable function (no non-local control flow) and to mark that the branch body is meaningful. OS_SUCCESS — The constant used in the comparison; its definition is needed to interpret the if condition and return value classification. OS_INVALID_POINTER — Common value used by pointer-check macros; include to understand what OS_CHECK_POINTER might return and whether that produces an early return. osal_id_t, OS_time_t, OS_object_token_t, int32 — Type definitions used in the function signature and local variables; required to parse the function and any macro expansions that depend on type. OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR — Constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to understand whether these arguments affect OS_ObjectIdGetById behavior (e.g. cause it to always fail) and therefore whether the branch can be reached.
